    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "Three of those whom Ezra sent to fetch Levites to accompany him to Jerusalem. Ezra 8:\n4. Son of Neriah, and faithful secretary to Jeremiah. He was eventually carried with Jeremiah into Egypt. Jer. 32: 12-16; Jer. 36: 4-32; Jer. 43: 3, 6; Jer. 45: 1,\n4. BATANAEA, on the south-east, now called Ard el Bathanyeh. The four districts have relics of a numerous population, with massive houses built of stone in some parts. THE OAKS OF BASHAN are used symbolically for great strength and loftiness, which God in His judgement brings down. Isa. 2: 13; Ezek. 27: 6; Zech. 11:\n4. In the earlier narrative, Gen. 26: 34; Gen. 28: 9, the names of Esau's wives differ from those given in Gen. 36: 2,\n4. Bathsheba. [Bath'sheba] Daughter of Eliam, or Ammiel, and wife of Uriah the Hittite. David `[char_David_Rut_4]`'s lusting after her became the occasion of his sin in accomplishing the death of her husband. She afterwards became David `[char_David_Rut_4]`'s wife and was the mother of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` and other children. When Adonijah sought to make himself king, Bathsheba, moved by Nathan, appealed to David `[char_David_Rut_4]` to fulfil his promise to her that Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` should be his successor. When Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` was king Adonijah begged Bathsheba to use her influence to obtain Abishag for him as wife. She asked this of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`, but it led to Adonijah's death. 2 Sam. 11: 3; 2 Sam. 12: 24; 1 Kings 1: 11-31; 1 Kings 2: 13-19; Ps. 51 title . Bathshua. [Bath'-shua] Another name for BATHSHEBA, the wife of David `[char_David_Rut_4]`. 1 Chr. 3:\n4. Ezra in great grief at the sin of the people plucked off the hair of his head and of his beard. Ezra 9: 3: cf. Jer. 41:",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "The \u201cseventy\u201d can only be obtained by adding Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`, Manasseh, and Ephraim; but of course, this leaves out Dinah (vs. 15)! Since Dinah and Serah or Dinah and Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` have to be omitted in the total of sixty-six and seventy, we have the clue to Stephen\u2019s \u201cseventy-five\u201d without consulting any scholar who ever lived in Alexandria, who was connected with Alexandria, who was educated at Alexandria, or who ever worshipped Alexandria.",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "I will go down with thee into Egypt, etc.] Which was enough to silence all his fears; for if the presence of God went with him to protect and defend hide, to bless and prosper him, and to direct, support, and comfort, he had nothing to fear from any quarter: and I will also surely bring thee up [again]: Jarchi takes this to be a promise that he should be buried in the land of Canaan, which had its fulfilment, when his corpse was carried out of Egypt to Machpelah, and there interred; but rather this refers to the bringing up of his posterity from thence in due time, for which Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` might be most solicitous, and so the Targum of Jonathan, \u201cand I will bring up thy children from thence:\u201d and Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` shall put his hand upon thine eyes: and so close them when he was dead; this, as Aben Ezra says, was a custom of the living to the dead, and it used to be done by the nearest relations and friends, though now with us commonly by strangers, or those that are not akin: this was a custom among the Greeks and Romans, as appears from Homer f1809, Virgil f1810, Ovid f1811, and other writers f1812; and so, among the Jews, Tobias is said to shut the eyes of his wife\u2019s father and mother, and to bury them honourably, \u201cWhere he became old with honour, and he buried his father and mother in law honourably, and he inherited their substance, and his father Tobit\u2019s.\u201d (Tobit 14:13) Of the Vulgate Latin version: Maimonides f1813 reckons this of closing the eyes of the dead, among the rites used towards them, and so in the Talmud 772 f1814: now by this expression Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` was assured that Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` was alive, and that he should live to see him, and that Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` would outlive him, and do this last office for him; and, as Ben Melech observes, by this he had the good news told him that Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` should remain behind him, to sustain and support his sons, and his sons\u2019 sons, all the years that he should live after him.\nVer."
