    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "The MITER (vss. 37, 39, and 39:28). The miter is connected with the high priest, both in the English text of Zechariah 3:5 and the Hebrew text of Ezekiel 21:\n6. The MITER (vss. 37, 39, and 39:28). The miter is connected with the high priest, both in [v_Zec_3_5] the English text of Zechariah 3:5 and the Hebrew text of [v_Ezk_21_26] Ezekiel 21:",
    "E.W. Bullinger": "It is this \"first love\" which Israel is here charged with having \"left.\"\nThis is the beginning of all the subsequent evil.\nEPHESUS\nSMYRNA\nIn Smyrna, we have a reference to a definite time of trial.. In the wilderness it was forty\nyears. Here it is ten days. If any wish to make this stand for ten years it must be on their own\nresponsibility. We only press the point that a corresponding time of trial is referred to; and\nthat it is a definite and limited time.\nWe are aware of the \"interpretation\" proposed as to there having been ten persecutions\nof \"Christians\" between A.D. 57 and",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And they took their cattle, and their goods, which they had gotten in the land of Canaan, etc.] Some interpreters add, by way of explanation, and in Mesopotamia; much of Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s substance being yet there, though the greatest part was got in Canaan, and so that is put for the whole; and Jarchi supposes that Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` gave all that he got in Padanaram to Esau for his part in the cave of Machpelah, and therefore mention is only made of his substance in Canaan; but there is no need of any such additions or suppositions, since the text only speaks of the substance of Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s sons, and what they had was only gotten in Canaan, into which they came very young; all which they brought with them as being their property, and not obliged to leave it behind to strangers; though they were bid not to regard their stuff, yet they were not willing to live upon others, but upon their own, and as much as they could independent of others; and that they might not be upbraided hereafter that they came into Egypt poor and destitute of everything: and came into Egypt, Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`, and all his seed with him; safe and well. 773\nVer."
